{
  "id": "schizophrenia-spectrum",
  "title": "Schizophrenia Spectrum Disorders",
  "subtitle": "Psychosis, Delusions, and the Five Disorders",
  "summary": "The schizophrenia spectrum includes five distinct disorders that share psychotic symptoms but differ in duration, functioning level, and symptom complexity. Schizophrenia (≥6 months, chronic), schizophreniform (1-6 months), schizoaffective (psychosis + mood episodes), brief psychotic disorder (1 day to <1 month, full recovery), and delusional disorder (only delusions, functioning intact) form a spectrum distinguished primarily by time course and symptom pattern.",
  "keyTakeaways": [
    "Duration is the PRIMARY diagnostic differentiator: <1 month = brief psychotic, 1-6 months = schizophreniform, ≥6 months = schizophrenia.",
    "Delusional disorder has ONLY delusions with NO hallucinations, disorganized speech, or negative symptoms - and functioning remains intact outside the delusion.",
    "Schizoaffective requires BOTH psychotic symptoms AND mood episodes (depression or mania) - not just schizophrenia with some sadness.",
    "Positive symptoms ADD abnormal experiences (hallucinations, delusions); Negative symptoms REMOVE normal functions (emotion, motivation).",
    "Clanging is a specific disorganized speech pattern where words are connected by rhyme/sound rather than meaning."
  ],
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Overview: Five Disorders, One Spectrum"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The schizophrenia spectrum contains five disorders that share psychotic symptoms but differ in critical ways. Understanding these differences is essential for accurate diagnosis."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "title": "The Five Schizophrenia Spectrum Disorders",
      "items": [
        "Schizophrenia: Chronic psychosis lasting ≥6 months with significant functional decline. Includes positive symptoms (delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech) and negative symptoms (flat affect, reduced motivation).",
        "Schizophreniform Disorder: SAME symptoms as schizophrenia but duration is only 1-6 months. Can progress to schizophrenia if symptoms persist past 6 months.",
        "Schizoaffective Disorder: Psychotic symptoms PLUS mood episodes (major depression or mania). Both conditions present together, not just schizophrenia with low mood.",
        "Brief Psychotic Disorder: Sudden onset psychosis lasting 1 day to <1 month. Often triggered by stress. Full recovery to baseline functioning expected.",
        "Delusional Disorder: ONLY delusions (≥1 month). No hallucinations, disorganized speech, or negative symptoms. Functioning remains intact outside the delusional belief system."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "Info",
      "title": "Duration Timeline - Memorize This",
      "text": "1 day to <1 month = Brief Psychotic Disorder | 1-6 months = Schizophreniform | ≥6 months = Schizophrenia. Duration is the single most important diagnostic criterion separating these three disorders."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Schizophrenia: The Chronic Disorder"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Schizophrenia requires psychotic symptoms persisting for at least 6 months with significant decline in functioning. It affects multiple brain systems, producing both positive and negative symptoms."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "title": "Positive Symptoms (Adding Abnormal Experiences)",
      "items": [
        "Delusions: Fixed false beliefs maintained despite contradictory evidence. Types include persecutory (being harmed), reference (events have special personal meaning), grandiose (exceptional powers), control (external forces controlling thoughts), and somatic (bodily abnormalities).",
        "Hallucinations: Sensory experiences without external stimuli. Auditory hallucinations (hearing voices) are MOST common in schizophrenia - the person hears sounds that aren't there but experiences them as completely real.",
        "Disorganized Speech: Speech that doesn't follow logical connections. Includes 'clanging' - connecting words by rhyme or sound rather than meaning.",
        "Disorganized Behavior: Unpredictable, inappropriate actions that interfere with daily functioning."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "title": "Negative Symptoms (Removing Normal Functions)",
      "items": [
        "Flat Affect: Complete absence of emotional expression - face shows no emotion, voice is monotone.",
        "Blunt Affect: Reduced emotional expression - emotions are present but dampened/muted.",
        "Inappropriate Affect: Emotional expression that doesn't match the situation - laughing at sad news, crying at jokes.",
        "Avolition: Loss of motivation and initiative - person stops pursuing goals or activities.",
        "Alogia: Poverty of speech - brief, empty responses lacking elaboration."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "AlertCircle",
      "title": "Why 'Positive' and 'Negative'?",
      "text": "These terms don't mean 'good' and 'bad.' Positive symptoms ADD something that shouldn't be there (hallucinations, delusions - these are 'additions' to normal experience). Negative symptoms SUBTRACT something that should be there (emotions, motivation - these are 'losses' from normal functioning)."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Clanging: A Concrete Example"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Clanging demonstrates how disorganized speech works in schizophrenia. The person connects words based on how they SOUND rather than what they MEAN. Here's an actual clinical example:"
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "Info",
      "title": "Clinical Dialogue - Clanging",
      "text": "Therapist: 'What color is your dress?' Patient: 'Red... Like a bed.' Therapist: 'Why is it like a bed?' Patient: 'Because it's dead.' Therapist: 'Why is a bed like being dead?' Patient: 'I dunno... maybe it's a med.' Therapist: 'What's a med?' Patient: 'A bled.' Notice: red → bed → dead → med → bled. Each word rhymes with the previous one. The patient's brain is connecting words by SOUND pattern, not logical meaning."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Seven Types of Delusions"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "title": "Delusion Types with Examples",
      "items": [
        "Persecutory: Belief that others are harming, watching, or targeting you. Example: 'The FBI is monitoring me through my laptop.'",
        "Delusions of Reference: Belief that neutral events have special personal significance. Example: 'The news anchor was sending me coded messages.'",
        "Grandiose: Belief of having exceptional power, identity, or abilities. Example: 'I am secretly royalty and will inherit a kingdom.'",
        "Delusions of Control: Belief that external forces control your thoughts or actions. Includes thought insertion (thoughts put into your mind), thought withdrawal (thoughts removed from your mind), and thought broadcasting (your thoughts transmitted to others).",
        "Somatic: False beliefs about bodily functions or abnormalities. Example: 'I have parasitic worms in my intestines' (despite negative tests).",
        "Nihilistic: Belief that oneself, others, or the world doesn't exist or has ended. Example: 'The world ended and everyone is just an illusion.'",
        "Erotomanic: Belief that someone (often a celebrity) is secretly in love with you. Example: 'The famous actor sends me love messages through his TV interviews.'"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Delusional Disorder: Only Delusions, Functioning Intact"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Delusional disorder is fundamentally different from schizophrenia. The person has delusions lasting at least 1 month, but NO other psychotic symptoms (no hallucinations, no disorganized speech/behavior, no negative symptoms). Most importantly: functioning is INTACT outside the delusional belief system."
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "Info",
      "title": "Functioning Comparison",
      "text": "Schizophrenia: Significant decline across multiple life areas - often cannot maintain employment, relationships deteriorate, self-care suffers. Delusional Disorder: Person works full-time, dresses appropriately, has normal conversations - the ONLY problem is their fixed false belief. Example: A bus driver with persecutory delusions (believes neighbors are recording him) still works every day without issues."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Schizoaffective Disorder: Two Problems Together"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Schizoaffective disorder requires BOTH: (1) psychotic symptoms meeting schizophrenia criteria, AND (2) major mood episodes (depression or mania). This isn't just 'schizophrenia plus feeling sad' - the person must have full mood episodes that meet diagnostic criteria."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "title": "Schizoaffective vs. Similar Conditions",
      "items": [
        "vs. Schizophrenia: Schizoaffective includes prominent mood episodes; schizophrenia does not.",
        "vs. Bipolar with Psychotic Features: In bipolar, psychosis ONLY occurs DURING mood episodes. In schizoaffective, psychosis persists even WHEN there's no mood episode happening.",
        "Key distinction: If you removed the mood episodes, would psychotic symptoms remain? Yes = schizoaffective. No = mood disorder with psychotic features."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Brief Psychotic Disorder: Temporary Break, Full Recovery"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Brief psychotic disorder involves sudden onset of psychotic symptoms lasting at least 1 day but less than 1 month. It often occurs after extreme stress. The key feature: COMPLETE return to baseline functioning after the episode ends."
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "Info",
      "title": "Clinical Example - Brief Psychotic Disorder",
      "text": "A 24-year-old student, after failing exams and having a major argument, suddenly becomes convinced the FBI is monitoring her laptop and classmates are government agents poisoning her food. She screams at 'agents' and barely sleeps for 5 days. After 12 days with low-dose medication and therapy, all symptoms completely disappear. She returns fully to baseline with good insight that the episode was stress-related. This is brief psychotic disorder: stress trigger, short duration (12 days), complete recovery."
    }
  ],
