      "answer": "Brief psychotic disorder",
      "explanation": {
        "correct": "This is brief psychotic disorder. The key features: (1) Sudden onset after identifiable stressors (exams, argument), (2) Duration of 12 days - longer than 1 day but less than 1 month, (3) Full psychotic symptoms during episode (delusions, behavioral disturbance), (4) COMPLETE resolution with treatment, (5) Return to baseline functioning, (6) Good insight afterward. Brief psychotic disorder is often stress-triggered and has excellent prognosis - the person recovers fully. The short duration (<1 month) and complete recovery distinguish it from schizophreniform or schizophrenia.",
        "incorrect": {
          "Schizophrenia": "Schizophrenia requires symptoms lasting ≥6 months and typically involves chronic course without full recovery. This patient had symptoms for only 12 days and recovered completely. Also, schizophrenia doesn't typically have clear stress triggers or full resolution.",
          "Schizophreniform disorder": "Schizophreniform requires 1-6 months of symptoms. At only 12 days, this episode is too SHORT for schizophreniform. The diagnosis is duration-dependent: <1 month = brief psychotic, 1-6 months = schizophreniform.",
          "Delusional disorder": "Delusional disorder involves ONLY delusions (no behavioral disturbance, no emotional symptoms) with INTACT functioning. This patient showed multiple symptoms (terror, screaming, sleep disturbance, behavioral changes) and significant functional impairment during the episode."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "question": "What distinguishes delusional disorder from schizophrenia in terms of functioning?",
