      "answer": "In delusional disorder, functioning is intact OUTSIDE the delusion system; schizophrenia involves global functional decline",
      "explanation": {
        "correct": "This is a critical distinction. In delusional disorder, the person functions normally in ALL areas EXCEPT those directly related to their delusion. A bus driver with persecutory delusions (neighbors recording him) still drives every day, has normal conversations, dresses appropriately. The delusion is 'encapsulated' - contained within one belief system. Schizophrenia causes GLOBAL decline - problems with work, relationships, self-care, across multiple domains. The person with schizophrenia typically cannot maintain employment or independent living.",
        "incorrect": {
          "Delusional disorder always leads to hospitalization while schizophrenia doesn't": "This is backwards. People with delusional disorder often NEVER get hospitalized because they function normally and may not seek help. Schizophrenia more commonly requires hospitalization due to severe functional impairment and safety concerns.",
